I think a lot about the millennials who were the last generation to be able to create connections with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during the golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We dove directly into things without having to worry about the source, because it wasn't that easy to determine.
Without having a reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships had become the foundation of our lives.
That's why we're so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the series every Thursday.
It looked like nothing compared to what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in designated closed spaces.
Unconsciously we died of envy to connect to the universal community that surrounded all of this
That's why we're all so obsessed with watching series like The Office or movies like Présentateur vedette, with plenty of short references, like memes.
We repeated these refs, knowing that most people knew them
Now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
There are too many things to see and no way to rationalize them all... will we escape the hypersaturation?
We get caught up in cycles of discovering new media, just to realize that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
We're forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while recognizing that the people who created the art we connect to can be very imperfect.
We enter parasocial relationships with more attention.
We understand that it's hard to arrive at these positions of wealth and power without stepping on others along the way.
due to a lack of collective consciousness about the media, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us to remain critical.
some of us continue to put people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall off.
we are in a tumultuous period and I'm looking forward to seeing where it will take us.
